<br>
But, I'm having hard time trying to see, what's there keeping people interested in it for 5+ years. What's there to give sense of accomplishment? If everything is there when you're ready for it. I played Diablo2 and DS after I was hooked up in EQ, and both games were so disappointing. They were short, easy and anti-climatic. Once you reached the end, that was it. Looking at WoW and the lack of all those features that people think they hate in EQ, it just looks to me as expanded single-player game.<br>
<br>
Let's take VT key as an example... yes, it takes luck and time to get it. (Luck cuts down time). But once you combine it and zone into VT, it pays off. *shrug* Now, without time sinks, you just walk to your quest giver, run off to collect/talk/whatever and return. Remember, no camping, so pieces drop if you have enough force to keel target00. Based on that, making a guild VT ready would've taken 2 days after the launch. VT would've been farmed in 2 weeks... then what? Since there are no timesinks, what are rarer quests going to be? Probably those you get once in a blue moon, if you're lucky camping the quest giver. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Now, I know there are dedicated people working on WoW. So based on tidbits of information, my perception may be very wrong. I just haven't gotten my hopes skyhigh yet. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
